    Trigger in MySQL
A Trigger is a set of SQL statements that automatically executes when a specific event happens on a table
-> A trigger is an automatic action performed by the database when data is inserted, updated, or deleted

Ex: Think of a bank transaction system:
When money is deposited -> update balance automatically
When money is withdrawn -> log transaction(Antee store anii)
You don't manually run queries — it happens automatically, that's a trigger understood?

Triggers are based on events:
 Events     When it happens      
 INSERT | New row added        
 UPDATE | Existing row changed 
 DELETE | Row removed          

Types:
 BEFORE | Runs before operation 
 AFTER  | Runs after operation  

Types of Triggers (Important for SPARK):
 Type                Example  chudandi                   
 BEFORE INSERT | Validate data before insert 
 AFTER INSERT  | Log new entry               
 BEFORE UPDATE | Check conditions            
 AFTER UPDATE  | Audit changes               
 BEFORE DELETE | Prevent deletion            
 AFTER DELETE  | Log deletion                

Basic Syntax: 
DELIMITER //

CREATE TRIGGER trigger_name
BEFORE/AFTER INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE
ON table_name
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN

    Write SQL logic;

END //

DELIMITER ;

Types of Triggers:
1. BEFORE INSERT Trigger
Example 1: Ensure rent is not negative

DELIMITER //
CREATE TRIGGER before_insert_rent
BEFORE INSERT
ON properties
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN

    IF NEW.rent < 0 THEN
        SET NEW.rent = 0;
    END IF;

END //
DELIMITER ; /* NEW.rent - incoming value
If rent is invalid -> correct it */

2. AFTER INSERT Trigger
Example2: Log every new property added

Create log table:
CREATE TABLE property_log (
    log_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    property_id INT,
    action VARCHAR(50),
    log_time TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);

Ippudu Trigger create cheyandi:
DELIMITER //
CREATE TRIGGER after_insert_property
AFTER INSERT
ON properties
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN

INSERT INTO property_log(property_id, action)
VALUES (NEW.property_id, 'INSERT');

END //

DELIMITER ;
Usecases: Audit logs, Tracking changes, Debugging kosam

3. AFTER UPDATE Trigger
Example3: Track rent changes
DELIMITER //

CREATE TRIGGER after_update_rent
AFTER UPDATE
ON properties
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN

IF OLD.rent <> NEW.rent THEN
    INSERT INTO property_log(property_id, action)
    VALUES (NEW.property_id, 'RENT UPDATED');
END IF;

END //

DELIMITER ;

4. BEFORE DELETE Trigger
Prevent deletion of expensive properties
DELIMITER //

CREATE TRIGGER before_delete_property
BEFORE DELETE
ON properties
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN

IF OLD.rent > 100000 THEN
    SIGNAL SQLSTATE '45000'
    SET MESSAGE_TEXT = 'Cannot delete premium property';
END IF;

END //

DELIMITER ;

5. AFTER DELETE Trigger
Example5: Log deleted properties
DELIMITER //

CREATE TRIGGER after_delete_property
AFTER DELETE
ON properties
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN

INSERT INTO property_log(property_id, action)
VALUES (OLD.property_id, 'DELETED');

END //

DELIMITER ;

